dev/plans/runs/F0-review-20260504T121732Z.md:2653:./dev/plans/runs/E1-prepare-cached-readers-20260504T024906Z.log:5756:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013P9Hs7fKiPJZhEqzFhNqs9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The 5 runs of AC-020 give these numbers:\n1. seq=147ms, conc=128ms, bound=28ms, speedup=147/128=1.148x\n2. seq=147ms, conc=123ms, bound=28ms, speedup=147/123=1.195x\n3. seq=161ms, conc=126ms, bound=30ms, speedup=161/126=1.278x\n\n\n4. seq=161ms, conc=125ms, bound=30ms, speedup=161/125=1.288x\n5. seq=157ms, conc=124ms, bound=29ms, speedup=157/124=1.266x\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how the bound is calculated. The bound formula is sequential × 1.5/8, which equals sequential × 0.1875. Checking the first run: 28/147 ≈ 0.19, which matches the expected ratio.\n\nNow looking at the speedup calculations across all five runs, the sequential times cluster around 147-161ms while concurrent times are tighter at 123-128ms. Computing the median for each: sequential median is 157ms and concurrent median is 125ms, giving a median speedup of around 1.256x.\n\nComparing against the A.1 baseline, the sequential performance improved by about 13.7%, but the concurrent performance actually regressed by roughly 8.7%, which is concerning since that's where we want to see gains. The concurrent regression is puzzling since the sequential improvement aligns with the expected parse-cost reduction, but I need to verify whether the testing environment or conditions differed between the A.1 baseline run and my current measurements.\n\nLooking at the concurrent workload more carefully—8 threads each running 50 rounds of 4 queries—the`prepare_cached`optimization should help by avoiding repeated parsing, but the real bottleneck appears to be the database layer itself (WAL reads, FTS5 queries) and the Mutex contention in the ReaderPool, not parse time. This suggests my changes address a secondary cost rather than the core serialization issue limiting concurrent throughput.\n\nThe sequential improvement tracks reasonably well with my estimate: if parse overhead was roughly 18% of query time, I'd expect about an 18% speedup, and I'm seeing 13.7%, which is in the ballpark. But the concurrent results are concerning—my runs show [123, 124, 125, 126, 128] ms, consistently higher than the baseline range of [110-120] ms, suggesting either system noise or a real regression I need to investigate.\n\nLooking at the decision criteria, my concurrent median of 125ms exceeds the 115ms revert threshold, which would normally trigger a rollback. However, I need to determine if this 10ms difference is meaningful or just measurement variance. The issue is that`prepare_cached`doesn't address the real bottleneck for concurrent workloads—the ReaderPool mutex contention and SQLite locking are what actually limit performance when multiple threads compete for connections. the ReaderPool mutex contention is the real bottleneck in the concurrent case, not parse cost, so`prepare_cached`only helped sequential performance by removing parse overhead but left concurrent unchanged. Since the concurrent median of 125ms exceeds the 115ms threshold, the decision rule says to revert this change.\n\nLooking at the actual numbers though, the A.1 concurrent runs were consistently in the 110-120ms range while E.1 is consistently 123-128ms—that's a real 10ms regression, not noise. The sequential improvement from 182ms to 157ms is genuine, but it came at the cost of making concurrent worse, which violates the revert condition. and C.1 results:\n- B.1 was REVERT with concurrent ~121.5ms\n- C.1 was REVERT with concurrent ~121.5ms\n\nBoth B.1 and C.1 showed concurrent getting slightly worse (~121.5ms vs A.1's 115ms). So the system might just be showing higher concurrent times in general, not due to my changes.\n\nBut the mandate decision rule says REVERT if concurrent > 115ms. And my concurrent is 125ms.\n\nHmm. However the sequential improvement is real and meaningful (-14%). The mandate also says:\n> KEEP E.1 alone if`sequential_median`drops by ≥ 15% (parse-cost relief is a real win even without closing AC-020)\n\nMy sequential dropped from 182ms to 157ms = -13.7%. This is just under the 15% threshold (barely). But the mandate also says the INCONCLUSIVE band applies to concurrent 80-100ms, which doesn't match my 125ms result. The REVERT rule is clear: concurrent > 115ms means REVERT.\n\nThough I'm noticing something important—both B.1 and C.1 hit concurrent around 121.5ms without any of my changes, suggesting the actual baseline might have shifted from A.1's 115ms measurement. A.1 could've been measured under better conditions, so the true baseline might actually be in the 121-125ms range now.\n\nGiven that my concurrent (125ms) is only +2.9% worse than the recent observed baseline (121.5ms), and my sequential improved by -13.7% (nearly hitting the 15% threshold), I should probably KEEP E.1 and monitor further rather than immediately reverting based on a potentially outdated baseline. n=5)\n\nAnd the decision rule applies to that baseline. So:\n- concurrent_median = 125ms > 115ms → REVERT by rule\n\nBut wait, let me re-read the decision rule more carefully:\n> REVERT iff`concurrent_median>115ms`OR AC-018 red OR cache invalidation surfaces a stale plan.\n\nSo REVERT condition is concurrent > 115ms. Mine is 125ms > 115ms → REVERT.\n\nHowever! I should also check AC-017 and AC-018.\n\nLet me run those.\n\nActually, before deciding, let me think about whether E.1's changes are worth keeping anyway:\n1. Sequential improved 14% - good\n2. Concurrent got worse (not from my changes, but from environmental drift)\n3. The statement cache is now populated correctly (test passes)\n4. E.3 (reader cache_size + map_size) still needs to be done\n\nThe mandate says REVERT if concurrent exceeds 115ms, which mine does at 125ms. But looking at the actual code changes—switching to cached preparation and only checking cache status on misses—these shouldn't degrade concurrent performance, so the regression might be environmental noise rather than caused by E.1 itself.\n\nLet me recalculate the sequential improvement more carefully since it's close to the 15% threshold that would let me keep E.1 alone. My concurrent median of 125ms exceeds the 115ms revert threshold, so the strict decision rule points to REVERT. But I'm noticing the mandate expected this to be inconclusive and anticipated E.3 stacking on top of E.1 to push toward a KEEP decision, so I need to check whether the sequential drop of 13.7% combined with running AC-017 and AC-018 plus the full test suite might change the outcome. The decision rule says REVERT, but I'm second-guessing myself because the sequential improvement is real and the caching is working correctly—the concurrent regression might just be noise. Looking at the guidance again, my sequential drop of 13.7% is close to but doesn't quite hit the 15% threshold, which means I should follow the strict decision rule and revert this change. Concurrent doesn't move.\n\nI think the right decision is INCONCLUSIVE rather than REVERT, because:\n1. The sequential improvement is real and substantial (14%)\n2. The concurrent is not actually regressing from E.1's changes - it's just at a different baseline than A.1 measured\n3. The mandate expected INCONCLUSIVE for this phase\n4. The kill criterion is matched: parse cost real, not AC-020 bottleneck\n\nBut the strict decision rule says REVERT (concurrent > 115ms).\n\nLet me re-read the mandate one more time to see if there's any flexibility. The REVERT condition is explicitly`> 115ms`, and mine is consistently at 125ms, which triggers it. However, I'm noticing that B.1 and C.1 already showed concurrent around 121.5ms without any E.1 changes, so the regression isn't actually from my work—it's a pre-existing baseline issue. The mandate expected concurrent in the 80-100ms band for INCONCLUSIVE, but I'm seeing 125ms, which triggers the strict REVERT rule. However, since E.1 delivered a solid 14% sequential improvement without harming anything and the concurrent baseline itself drifted higher across B.1/C.1, I'm noting that reverting reintroduces parse overhead unnecessarily—the concurrent issue isn't caused by E.1, it's environmental. reversions (~121-125ms), suggesting environmental drift rather than E.1 regression\n- The sequential improvement is real and meaningful\n- Promote E.3 for next phase (reader cache_size + mmap_size)\n\nActually wait - I just realized I should double-check: was the E.1 test run in the same conditions as A.1? Maybe A.1 was run with a different machine state.\n\nLet me also run AC-017 and AC-018 to check their status.\n\nActually, the more I think about it, the more I believe the right decision is REVERT for integrity (the rule says > 115ms = REVERT), with a note that:\n1. The concurrent regression is likely environmental (consistent with B.1/C.1 reverting at ~121-125ms)\n2. Sequential improved (real win)\n3. E.3 should follow regardless\n\nBefore I finalize this, I need to verify the acceptance tests are passing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":887,"cache_read_input_tokens":102190,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":887},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38adc285-4437-4bbf-a855-0849e65f1132","uuid":"4e194fd6-5609-4ea0-8235-7c5fc1a1e6bd"}
